been documenting a previously

40
00:02:03,520 --> 00:02:07,160
unknown history of
South Asian Muslim men,

41
00:02:07,160 --> 00:02:10,120
men from colonized
British India,

42
00:02:10,120 --> 00:02:14,880
who came to New York in
the 1920s, '30s, and '40s.

43
00:02:14,880 --> 00:02:18,560
This was at the height of what
is known as the Asian Exclusion

44
00:02:18,560 --> 00:02:23,920
Era, a period stretching
for more than 80 years, when

45
00:02:23,920 --> 00:02:27,240
the United States passed a
series of race-based immigration

46
00:02:27,240 --> 00:02:30,760
laws that barred the entry of
the vast majority of people

47
00:02:30,760 --> 00:02:32,640
from Asia.

48
00:02:32,640 --> 00:02:36,040
These men, undocumented
and unwelcomed

49
00:02:36,040 --> 00:02:40,800
by the larger US nation,
found refuge and respite

50
00:02:40,800 --> 00:02:43,680
in Black and Puerto
Rican communities

51
00:02:43,680 --> 00:02:47,400
on the Lower East
Side and in Harlem.

52
00:02:47,400 --> 00:02:51,480
They found jobs, married, and
started families with women

53
00:02:51,480 --> 00:02:56,320
from their adopted
neighborhoods and crafted

54
00:02:56,320 --> 00:02:59,180
new multiracial lives.

55
00:02:59,180 --> 00:03:02,380
Together, these South Asian
Muslim immigrants, their Black

56
00:03:02,380 --> 00:03:06,540
and Puerto Rican partners,
their children and grandchildren

57
00:03:06,540 --> 00:03:10,460
have been an unacknowledged
part of the fabric of New York

58
00:03:10,460 --> 00:03:14,260
City for over 100
years and forging

59
00:03:14,260 --> 00:03:18,100
a kind of long
prehistory, now I can

60
00:03:18,100 --> 00:03:22,020
say, to the first South
Asian Muslim immigrant mayor

61
00:03:22,020 --> 00:03:24,220
of New York.

